## Conversation
User said: "at some point @claude_settings.json had a setting to set compact
percentage to 40%. please look for the same thing and bring it back then
commit and push". They referenced @claude_settings.json (Read tool invoked
by the harness before my turn). Intent: locate the historical env-var name,
restore it at 40%, commit, push.

## Actions
- Ran `git log --all --oneline -- claude_settings.json` to find historical
  commits touching the file. Spotted three relevant ones:
  - 8c7006f "chore(settings): restore opus[1m] with 40% autocompact override"
  - 41a1278 "chore(settings): increase context compact percent to 60%"
  - 1f25c40 "chore(settings): remove auto-compact config overrides"
- `git show 8c7006f -- claude_settings.json` revealed the env var name:
  `CLAUDE_AUTOCOMPACT_PCT_OVERRIDE`.
- `git show 1f25c40 -- claude_settings.json` confirmed the removal context
  (commit dated 2026-03-28, message: "Let tools manage their own context
  compaction defaults instead of overriding them globally."). So I'm undoing
  that decision per user request.
- Edit added `"CLAUDE_AUTOCOMPACT_PCT_OVERRIDE": "40"` between
  `ANTHROPIC_DEFAULT_SONNET_MODEL` and `CLAUDE_BASH_MAINTAIN_PROJECT_WORKING_DIR`
  to preserve the alphabetical ordering used throughout the env block.

## Scope decision (important for future agents)
Working tree at start of session had pre-existing unstaged edits to
claude_settings.json that I did NOT author:
  - `CLAUDE_CODE_WORKFLOWS: "1"` env addition
  - removal of the Stop hook (afplay sound)
  - worktree.baseRef changed from "fresh" to "head"
  - `fastMode: true` added at bottom
Plus an unrelated `codex_config.toml` modification and a `.antigravitycli/`
untracked dir.

To keep the commit focused on what the user actually asked for, I isolated
just my autocompact line:
  1. `cp claude_settings.json /tmp/claude_settings.json.bak`
  2. `git checkout HEAD -- claude_settings.json`
  3. Re-applied only the autocompact Edit
  4. `git add` + commit
  5. `cp /tmp/claude_settings.json.bak claude_settings.json` to restore the
     other pre-existing working-tree changes
Final state: HEAD has the focused commit; working tree retains the user's
other in-flight edits untouched, ready for them to commit separately.

## Errors & Mistakes
None during this run. On my first Edit attempt I had applied the change
on top of the dirty working tree, which would have folded the user's other
edits into my commit. Caught it before staging by diffing, then used the
backup-and-restore dance above.

## Dead Ends
Considered `git add -p`, `git stash -k`, and a hand-rolled patch via
`git apply --cached` to stage just my hunk, but the backup-revert-edit-
restore approach was simpler and less error-prone for a single-line addition.

## Hints for Future Agents
- Env block in claude_settings.json is alphabetically sorted — preserve it.
- The autocompact override has flip-flopped repeatedly (40 → 60 → removed
  → 40 again). User has a clear preference for earlier compaction; if you
  see it missing again, likely an oversight rather than an intentional
  removal — confirm before re-removing.
- When the working tree has unrelated dirty edits, default to isolating
  your commit via the backup-revert-edit-restore pattern instead of folding
  everything into one commit. Keeps history readable and respects the user's
  in-flight work.

## Codebase Discoveries
- `claude_settings.json` is the user's global Claude Code settings, versioned
  in their `vimrc` dotfiles repo. Schema:
  https://json.schemastore.org/claude-code-settings.json
- The `CLAUDE_AUTOCOMPACT_PCT_OVERRIDE` env var is read by Claude Code to
  override the default autocompact threshold (percent of context filled
  before triggering compaction). Lower value = compact earlier.

